{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> |name = Dark Star Safari |image = DarkStarSafari.jpg |border = yes |caption = First edition |author = [[Paul Theroux]] |cover_artist = |country = United States |language = English |genre = [[Non-fiction]] |publisher = [[Houghton Mifflin]] |release_date = 2002 |media_type = Print ([[Hardcover|Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) |pages = |isbn = }}
{{Listen| filename = Paul_theroux_in_bookclub_b039bg5h.flac |title = Theroux describes his reasons for revisiting Africa for the book |type = speech |description = from the BBC programme ''[[Bookclub (radio)|Bookclub]]'', September 1, 2013.<ref>{{Cite episode | title= Paul Theroux |series= Bookclub |serieslink= Bookclub (radio) |url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b039bg5h |station= [[BBC Radio 4]] |date= September 1, 2013 |accessdate= January 18, 2014 }}</ref> }}
'''''Dark Star Safari''''' (2002) is a written account of a trip taken by author [[Paul Theroux]] from [[Cairo, Egypt|Cairo]] to [[Cape Town]] via trains, buses, cars, and armed convoy.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/nov/02/featuresreviews.guardianreview9 Guardian.co.uk]</ref> Theroux had lived in Africa as a young and idealistic early member of the [[Peace Corps]]<ref>https://www.nytimes.com/2003/03/30/books/get-me-out-of-africa.html?pagewanted=2</ref> and part of the reason for this trip was to assess the impact on Africa of the many years of aid from Western countries. His assessment is generally critical of the long-term impact of aid programs.
Throughout the duration of the trip Theroux describes the writing of an erotic novella. This novella was eventually published in 2003, amongst a collection of short stories, as "The Stranger at the Palazzo D'Oro".
