{{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}} [[File:Piotr Bieńkowski.JPG|thumb|upright|Piotr Ignacy Bieńkowski.]] '''Piotr Ignacy Bieńkowski''' (1865 &ndash; 1925) was a [[Poland|Polish]] classical scholar and [[archaeologist]], [[professor]] of [[Jagiellonian University]].
Bieńkowski studied classical philology and history at the [[Lviv University|University of Lwów]] and [[University of Berlin]] (under [[Theodor Mommsen]]). He continued his studies in [[Vienna]], [[Rome]] and [[Athens]], habilitation at the [[University of Kraków]].
Piotr created at [[Kraków]] the first chair of classical archaeology at a Polish university. In the season of 1910-1911 as a representative of the [[Kraków Academy]], he took part in Austrian excavations conducted by Junker in [[el-Kubania]] heading the fieldwork at the Coptic monastery at a site called [[Mount of Isis]].
