'''Ł–l merger''' ({{lang-pl|bylaczenie}}) is a [[phonological change]] in northeastern dialects of [[Kashubian language]], a merger of [[Ł]] into [[L]].<ref name="LiC">{{cite book|author1=Dicky Gilbers |author2=John A. Nerbonne |author3=J. Schaeken |title=Languages in Contact |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QqQgBVXp_H4C&pg=PA331 |date=1 January 2000 |publisher=Rodopi |isbn=90-420-1322-2 |page=331}}</ref> The Polish-language term is derived from the pronunciation of the words "béł", "bëła" (Polish: "był", "była", English: "was") as "bél", "bëla".<ref name=karas>{{cite web|url=http://www.dialektologia.uw.edu.pl/index.php?l1=leksykon-kaszubski&lid=1089 |title=Dialektologia Polska |publisher=Dialektologia.uw.edu.pl |date= |accessdate=2013-12-31}}</ref> The corresponding group of dialects is called ''gwary bylackie''<!--cannot find english term-->.
The merger is attributed to the historical language contact with [[Low German]] being more intensive than with Polish compared to other Kashubian dialects.<ref name=LiC/>
==See also== *[[L-vocalization#Polish]] ([[:pl:wałczenie|wałczenie]]) ==References== {{reflist}}
